Three-Dimensional Vector Field MRE
For the MRE measurement, the experiment was run on a
standard 1.5T clinical MRI scanner (Siemens, Erlangen,
Germany). A head-cradle extended-piston driver was
used for 50 Hz harmonic head stimulation. A single-shot
spin-echo EPI sequence was developed for rapid 3D
motion field acquisition capable of acquiring a full set of
MRE data within less than 6 mins per volunteer. A full
set of MRE data consisted of 30 adjacent transverse
image slices with a 2

isotropic spatial reso-
lution (128

112 pixels). The three directions of the
encoding gradient provided the phase and the three Car-
tesian components of the displacement field at eight
equally spaced time steps over one vibration period, and
two averages were performed. The motion encoding gra-
dient was composed of three periods of a 60 Hz cosine
approximated by a trapezoidal shape providing the first
moment nulling.
Diffusion Tensor Imaging
For the fiber position measurement, diffusion tensor imag-
ing (DTI) data was acquired using a single-shot EPI
sequence (TR/TE-8500/96 ms) with 12 noncolinear direc-
tions and one

same as in MRE. Total acquisition time was 12 mins per
volunteer. Tensor calculation and tractography along the
CST was performed using the tools from the FMRIB Soft-
ware Library (FSL), i.e., dtifit and probtrackx (30). The cen-
tral part of the CST was obtained by tracking from a seed
region below the primary motor cortex to a target region in
the medulla oblongata, i.e., the pyramids that may be eas-
ily visualized in color coded fractional anisotropy maps.

can be observed that there is considerable variation in

lower regions, however, the average radius of the CSTs

corresponding velocity and attenuation for all five volun-
teers in both the right and left CSTs from the base to the
top of the FOV, while Fig. 6 shows the equivalent values
for the longitudinal coefficient, C
As can be observed, both the shear and longitudinal
coefficients vary as a function of position, decreasing in
stiffness as one moves from the base to the top of the
CST. Utilizing Eqs. 8 and 9 for the evaluation of the ve-
locity and attenuation, we see that the shear wave veloc-
ities range from 2 to 2.2 m/s, while the longitudinal
wave velocities range from around 5â7 m/s, and are
rather consistent with position until one reaches the top
of the pathways. There are two particular exceptions to
this concerning the right and left CSTs of Volunteer 1.
As shown in Fig. 3, there are serious bends near the top
of the fiber bundle (although the bending is not so
obvious in the left CST due to the perspective angle of
the image). As shown in Fig. 5e, this bend in the right
CST effects the shear wave velocity by inducing a slow-
ing as the shear wave makes the turn along the wave-
guide, and has an opposite effect on the longitudinal
wave velocity of the left CST as shown in Fig. 6f. The
causes of these anomalies are currently unknown and
will be addressed in future waveguide analysis.
There also appears to be a negative attenuation value
(i.e., an increase in wave amplitude) near the base of the
CST in virtually every volunteer and in both the longitu-
dinal and shear parameters. As this is very unusual
behavior, it was questioned whether the effects that are
being evaluated reflect genuine and interesting biological
features of waveguides, or whether they were simply a
consequence of the details of our methods. Upon further
analysis, it was observed that in this region, the CSTs
